Here’s a **compact, practical Kubernetes logging cheat sheet**, tailored for your setup (Infra + ServiceApp, namespace-based, multiple microservices).

You can **copy–paste this** and keep it handy 👇

---

# 🧾 Kubernetes Logging Cheat Sheet

> Assumes namespace: `job-scheduler`

```bash
NS=job-scheduler
```

---

## 🔹 1. Basic Pod Logs

### Logs of a single pod

```bash
kubectl logs <pod-name> -n $NS
```

### Follow logs (like `tail -f`)

```bash
kubectl logs -f <pod-name> -n $NS
```

### Last N lines

```bash
kubectl logs <pod-name> -n $NS --tail=100
```

---

## 🔹 2. Logs by Deployment (Most Used)

### Logs from all pods of a deployment

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/<deployment-name> -n $NS
```

### Follow deployment logs

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/<deployment-name> -n $NS -f
```

### Limit log lines

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/<deployment-name> -n $NS --tail=200
```

---

## 🔹 3. Logs by Label (Best for Microservices)

### Logs for pods with label

```bash
kubectl logs -l app=job-service -n $NS
```

### Follow logs with label

```bash
kubectl logs -l app=job-consumer -n $NS -f
```

---

## 🔹 4. Multi-Container Pod Logs

### List containers in a pod

```bash
kubectl get pod <pod-name> -n $NS -o jsonpath='{.spec.containers[*].name}'
```

### Logs from a specific container

```bash
kubectl logs <pod-name> -c <container-name> -n $NS
```

---

## 🔹 5. Previous / Crashed Pod Logs 🚨

### Logs from previous container instance

```bash
kubectl logs <pod-name> -n $NS --previous
```

### Very useful after crash / restart

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/job-consumer -n $NS --previous
```

---

## 🔹 6. Real-Time Debugging

### Stream logs + timestamps

```bash
kubectl logs -f <pod-name> -n $NS --timestamps
```

### Stream logs from all pods of a deployment

```bash
kubectl logs -f deployment/job-service -n $NS --all-containers=true
```

---

## 🔹 7. Infra Services Logs

### Kafka

```bash
kubectl logs -l app=kafka -n $NS
```

### MongoDB

```bash
kubectl logs -l app=mongodb -n $NS
```

### Postgres

```bash
kubectl logs -l app=postgres -n $NS
```

### Redis

```bash
kubectl logs -l app=redis -n $NS
```

---

## 🔹 8. ServiceApp Logs (Quick Access)

### Config Server

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/config-server -n $NS
```

### Service Discovery

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/service-discovery -n $NS
```

### API Gateway

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/api-gateway -n $NS -f
```

### Job Scheduler

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/job-scheduler -n $NS
```

### Job Service

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/job-service -n $NS -f
```

### Job Consumer

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/job-consumer -n $NS -f
```

### Job Executor (Cron)

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/jobexecutor-cron -n $NS
```

### Job Executor (Manual)

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/jobexecutor-manual -n $NS
```

---

## 🔹 9. Grep / Filter Logs 🔍

### Filter keyword

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/job-service -n $NS | grep ERROR
```

### Case-insensitive

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/job-service -n $NS | grep -i exception
```

---

## 🔹 10. Save Logs to File 📁

### Save pod logs

```bash
kubectl logs <pod-name> -n $NS > pod.log
```

### Save deployment logs

```bash
kubectl logs deployment/job-consumer -n $NS > job-consumer.log
```

---

## 🔹 11. Describe + Logs (Debug Combo)

```bash
kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n $NS
kubectl logs <pod-name> -n $NS
```

---

## 🔹 12. Most Useful One-Liners ⭐

```bash
# See crashing pods
kubectl get pods -n $NS | grep CrashLoopBackOff

# Logs of newest pod
kubectl logs $(kubectl get pods -n $NS --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp | tail -1 | awk '{print $1}') -n $NS

# Follow logs of everything (careful!)
kubectl logs -n $NS --all-containers=true -f -l app
```

---

## 🧠 Pro Tips

* Always **check labels**: `kubectl get pods --show-labels -n $NS`
* Use `--previous` after crashes
* Prefer **deployment logs** over pod logs in production
* For Kafka/DBs, logs often show **connection issues first**

